        "description": {
            "name": "description",
            "type": "java.lang.String",
            "value": "If both arguments of _formatAddress are emailadresses, this function creates an invalid Header.\r\nCalled like this: _formatAddress('jonas@email.de','jonas@email2.de') creates following return value: 'jonas@email2.de <jonas@email.de>'\r\nUsing this value as a Headervalue like \"From\", the From-Field is displayed incorrect. In Outlook the header looks like 'From: \"jonas@\" <email2.de jonas@email.de>'\r\n\r\nThis is because the name should be quoted.\r\n\r\nThe easiest way to fix it is to change the function like this:\r\n\r\n{code:title=Mail.php|borderStyle=solid}\r\nprotected function _formatAddress($email, $name)\r\n    {\r\n        if ($name === '' || $name === null || $name === $email) {\r\n            return $email;\r\n        } else {\r\n            $encodedName = $this->_encodeHeader($name);\r\n            if ($encodedName === $name && (strpos($name, ',') !== false || strpos($name, '@') !== false)) {\r\n                $format = '\"%s\" <%s>';\r\n            } else {\r\n                $format = '%s <%s>';\r\n            }\r\n            return sprintf($format, $encodedName, $email);\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n{code} \r\n\r\nGreetings,\r\nJonas"
        },
